sec.p:
Let $X \in R^{n \times p}$ be the normalized expression matrix (samples × genes). For gene iii, the Data Agent provides a DE summary
\begin{equation*}
\Delta_{i}=\left|\log _{2} F C_{i}\right|, \quad F D R_{i} \in(0,1].
\end{equation*}

The Pathway Miner Agent returns enriched pathways $\mathcal{P}= \left\{P_{1}, \ldots, P_{m}\right\}$ with $P_{k} \subseteq\{1, \ldots, p\}$ summarized by the incidence
\begin{equation*}
H_{i k}=\mathbf{1}\left\{i \in P_{k}\right\} \in\{0,1\}^{p \times m},
\end{equation*}

and the induced co-membership adjacency
\begin{equation*}
A=H H^{\top}, \quad A_{i j}=\sum_{k=1}^{m} 1\left\{i, j \in P_{k}\right\}.
\end{equation*}

The Weighting Agent composes statistical and network evidence. Define a DE-strength score and a centrality score:
\begin{equation*}
s_{i}^{D E}=\Delta_{i} \cdot\left(-\log _{10} F D R_{i}\right), \quad s_{i}^{c e n t}=\sum_{j=1}^{p} A_{i j}.
\end{equation*}

Let $r(\cdot)$ be a rank-normalization to [0], [1]. The final gene weight is:
\begin{equation*}
w_{i}=\alpha r!\left(s_{i}^{\text{DE}}\right)+\beta r!\left(s_{i}^{\text {cent }}\right), \quad \alpha, \beta \geq 0,
\end{equation*}

The Embedding Agent forms the weighted data $\tilde{X}=X W^{1 / 2}$ and computes a $d$-dimensional linear embedding by solving
\begin{equation*}
\tilde{X}=X W^{1 / 2}, \quad S_{w}=\frac{1}{n} \widetilde{X^{\top} \tilde{X}},
\end{equation*}

i.e., take the top $d$ eigenvectors of the weighted covariance $S_{w}$. Scores are $Z=X W^{1 / 2} U$ The fraction of variance explained is
\begin{equation*}
V E(d)=\frac{\sum_{k=1}^{d} \lambda_{k}\left(S_{w}\right)}{\sum_{k=1}^{p} \lambda_{k}\left(S_{w}\right)}.
\end{equation*}

This closed-form pathway-weighted PCA (wPCA) reorients principal directions toward pathway-coherent axes while preserving interpretability. A graph-regularized variant that encourages smoothness across the pathway graph is obtained by
\begin{equation*}
\max _{U^{\top} U=I} \operatorname{tr}\left(U^{\top} S_{w} U\right)-\lambda \operatorname{tr}\left(U^{\top} X^{\top} L X U\right), \quad \lambda \geq 0,
\end{equation*}

Finally, the design is embedding-agnostic. If is an encoder (autoencoder/VAE/transformer) with latent $Z=f_{\theta}(X)$, one can train with a base loss (reconstruction or contrastive) plus a pathway regularizer such as
\begin{equation*}
\begin{aligned}
\min _{\theta} \mathcal{L}_{\text{bs}}(X; \theta) & +\mu \operatorname{tr}\left(Z^{\top} L Z\right) \\
& -\eta \operatorname{tr}\left(Z^{\top} S_{w} Z\right), \quad \mu, \eta \geq 0
\end{aligned}
\end{equation*}
